From: PS3 Custom Toolchain
Subject: [PATCH] elf64-ppc: compact-OPD support for Cell OS Lv-2

CellOS Lv-2 uses a compact 8-byte function-descriptor format in .opd
([entry_ea_32, toc_ea_32] with R_PPC64_ADDR32 relocs at offsets 0 and 4,
4-byte alignment). Upstream binutils assumes 24-byte ELFv1 descriptors
(R_PPC64_ADDR64 + R_PPC64_TOC, 8-byte alignment). Two touchpoints need
compact-awareness for Lv-2 userland ELFs to link correctly:

  1. ppc64_elf_edit_opd() validates / rewrites .opd assuming the ELFv1
     layout; its checks reject compact descriptors as "not a regular
     array of opd entries". We skip the pass entirely for compact
     sections (detected by alignment_power < 3); they are small enough
     that the lost unused-entry trimming is not material.

  2. opd_entry_value() is the canonical way the linker walks a .opd
     entry to learn the callee's code-section address. Both the BL
     call-redirect path in ppc64_elf_relocate_section and the debug
     / addr2line plumbing route through this function. The upstream
     implementation dereferences the entry with bfd_get_64 in the
     no-relocs path and keys the relocs-path on a (R_PPC64_ADDR64,
     R_PPC64_TOC) pair; neither matches compact layout, so every
     `bl foo' where foo resolves to a compact OPD symbol silently
     falls through to a direct branch at the OPD's data address -
     the branch lands in .opd (W-A, no execute) and faults the
     instant the instruction fetches.

Fix: make opd_entry_value read the first 4 bytes as the callee entry
EA when the OPD section is compact, and accept a standalone
R_PPC64_ADDR32 at the entry offset (ignoring the paired TOC reloc at
+4) as the entry reloc. The BL-redirect path then works for compact
binaries exactly as it does for classic ELFv1.

--- a/bfd/elf64-ppc.c	2026-04-23 17:54:53.784004496 -0500
+++ b/bfd/elf64-ppc.c	2026-04-23 17:55:25.861197466 -0500
@@ -5578,7 +5578,15 @@
       if (offset + 7 >= opd_sec->size || offset + 7 < offset)
 	return (bfd_vma) -1;
 
-      val = bfd_get_64 (opd_bfd, contents + offset);
+      /* CellOS Lv-2 uses a compact 8-byte descriptor [entry_ea_32,
+	 toc_ea_32] at 4-byte alignment.  Upstream ELFv1 descriptors
+	 are 24-byte at 8-byte alignment.  Detect by alignment_power:
+	 < 3 means compact, read the 32-bit entry EA; otherwise read
+	 the 64-bit ELFv1 func field.  */
+      if (opd_sec->alignment_power < 3)
+	val = bfd_get_32 (opd_bfd, contents + offset);
+      else
+	val = bfd_get_64 (opd_bfd, contents + offset);
       if (code_sec != NULL)
 	{
 	  asection *sec, *likely = NULL;
@@ -5630,8 +5638,15 @@
 	{
 	  Elf_Internal_Shdr *symtab_hdr = &elf_symtab_hdr (opd_bfd);
 
-	  if (ELF64_R_TYPE (look->r_info) == R_PPC64_ADDR64
-	      && ELF64_R_TYPE ((look + 1)->r_info) == R_PPC64_TOC)
+	  /* Accept either the ELFv1 (R_PPC64_ADDR64, R_PPC64_TOC) pair
+	     or a Cell compact R_PPC64_ADDR32 at the entry offset (the
+	     paired R_PPC64_ADDR32 against .TOC. at +4 is the per-entry
+	     TOC slot and is not consulted here - the callee's code
+	     section is what we want to return).  */
+	  if ((ELF64_R_TYPE (look->r_info) == R_PPC64_ADDR64
+	       && ELF64_R_TYPE ((look + 1)->r_info) == R_PPC64_TOC)
+	      || (ELF64_R_TYPE (look->r_info) == R_PPC64_ADDR32
+		  && opd_sec->alignment_power < 3))
 	    {
 	      unsigned long symndx = ELF64_R_SYM (look->r_info);
 	      asection *sec = NULL;
@@ -7399,6 +7414,19 @@
       if (sec->output_section == bfd_abs_section_ptr)
 	continue;
 
+      /* CellOS Lv-2 uses a compact 8-byte .opd layout
+	 [entry_ea_32, toc_ea_32] with 4-byte alignment and only
+	 R_PPC64_ADDR32 relocations -- incompatible with the
+	 24-byte ELFv1 layout this pass assumes.  Detected via
+	 alignment power: ELFv1 .opd uses 8-byte alignment
+	 (power=3); compact .opd uses 4-byte (power=2).  Skip
+	 OPD optimisation entirely for compact sections; they
+	 are small enough that the lost optimisation does not
+	 matter.  The BL-redirect path in relocate_section still
+	 works for compact .opd via opd_entry_value().  */
+      if (sec->alignment_power < 3)
+	continue;
+
       /* Look through the section relocs.  */
       if ((sec->flags & SEC_RELOC) == 0 || sec->reloc_count == 0)
 	continue;
